{"title_page": "South West Rail Link", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width     = 300px\n| name          = '''South West Rail Link'''\n| other_name    = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| color         = \n| logo          = \n| logo_width    = 200px\n| logo_alt      = \n| image         = New South Wales metropolitan rail area, with South West Rail Link highlighted.svg\n| image_width   = 300px\n| image_alt     = \n| caption       = New South Wales Metropolitan Rail Area with South West Rail Link shuttle highlighted in pink\n| type          = \n| system        = \n| status        = \n| locale        = \n| start         = [[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield]]\n| end           = [[Leppington railway station|Leppington]]\n| stations      = 3\n| routes        = [[Inner West & Leppington Line|T2 Inner West & Leppington]]<br>[[Cumberland Line|T5 Cumberland]]\n| daily_ridership = \n| ridership2    = \n| open          = {{Start date|2015|02|08|df=y}}\n| close         = \n| owner         = [[RailCorp]]\n| operator      = [[Sydney Trains]]\n| depot         = \n| stock         = \n| linelength_km =  11.4\n| gauge = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electrification = [[Overhead line|Overhead]] 1500 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]]<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.asa.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/asa/asa-standards/t-hr-el-00001-ti.pdf|title=RailCorp electrical system general description, version 1.0|date=19 March 2014|author=Asset Standards Authority}}</ref>\n| speed =\n| website       = \n| map           = {{South West Rail Link RDT}}\n| map_state     = collapsed\n}}\n\nThe '''South West Rail Link''' is a railway line serving the developing suburbs of [[south-western Sydney]], Australia. Services form part of the [[Sydney Trains]] [[commuter rail]] network. It opened on 8 February 2015.\n\n==Description==\nThe line consists of a {{convert|11.4|km|abbr=on}} double-track railway, with stations in the suburbs of [[Leppington]] and [[Edmondson Park]]. The line is the major piece of public transport infrastructure for the Sydney metropolitan area's \"South West Growth Centre\". It connects with the rest of the Sydney rail network at [[Glenfield, New South Wales|Glenfield]], where services can continue north on the [[Main Southern railway line|Main South line]] or east on the [[East Hills railway line|East Hills line]]. Leppington station's four platforms can support frequent terminating services, even after an extension of the line. A train stabling facility to the west of the station further enhances this capability. Development of the project was managed by [[Transport for New South Wales]] and its predecessor, the [[Transport Construction Authority]].\n\n==History==\n===Conception===\nThe South West Rail Link was originally part of the Metropolitan Rail Expansion Program (MREP) proposed by the [[Bob Carr|Carr Government]] in 2005,<ref>{{cite news|last=Besser|first=Linton|title=Bye heavy rail, now for a north-west metro|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/bye-heavy-rail-now-for-a-northwest-metro/2008/02/25/1203788248514.html|accessdate=14 June 2011|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=26 February 2008}}</ref> along with the [[North West railway line, Sydney|North West Rail Link]] and the [[Redfern to Chatswood railway line|CBD rail link]]. The three projects were to be integrated into a single operational sector, with trains from the south-west running to the north-west via the CBD Link. The other two components of the MREP were cancelled in 2008, but the South West Rail Link remained on the government's agenda. Plans for the North West Rail Link were resurrected in 2011 and the rail link was completed in 2019, forming part of the [[Sydney Metro]] network.\n\nIn March 2008, the [[Morris Iemma|Iemma Government]] indicated that construction would begin in 2009, with completion scheduled for 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=New $1.36b rail link on time: Iemma|url= http://news.smh.com.au/national/new-136b-rail-link-on-time-iemma-20080306-1xe9.html|accessdate=14 June 2011|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 March 2008}}</ref> By October of that year the government had decided that delivery of the project would be divided into two stages. Stage one would comprise preliminary work around [[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield station]], and stage two would comprise construction of the new line itself, stage two was deferred due to budget cuts.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benson |first=Simon |title=Northwest Metro rail link officially shelved |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24579596-5001021,00.html |accessdate=14 June 2011 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=31 October 2008 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081103115958/http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24579596-5001021,00.html |archivedate=3 November 2008 }}</ref> On 14 November 2009, Premier [[Nathan Rees]] announced that construction of stage two of the South West Rail Link would begin in mid-2010, with completion scheduled for 2016.<ref name=CityRail3Dec09>[http://cityrail.info/news/2009/091203-southwest Green light for South West rail link Stage 2] [[CityRail]], 3 December 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Axed $1.3b south-west rail link revived|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/axed-13b-southwest-rail-link-revived-20091113-iept.html|accessdate=14 June 2011|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 November 2009|last1=Clennell|first1=Andrew|last2=Robins|first2=Brian}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\n====Stage one====\n[[File:Glenfield Railway Station Concourse Exterior.jpg|thumb|[[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield station]] new concourse building in December 2012]]\n[[File:Glenfield railway station carpark from south.jpg|thumb|[[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield station]] new multi-storey commuter car park in November 2011]]\nPlanning approval for stage one of the project was received in April 2009.<ref name=SWRLprofile>{{cite web|title=Project profile |url=http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/Our-Projects/Current-Projects/South-West-Rail-Link/Project-Profile/Project-profile/default.aspx|publisher=Transport Construction Authority |accessdate=14 June 2011 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906084033/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/Our-Projects/Current-Projects/South-West-Rail-Link/Project-Profile/Project-profile/default.aspx|archivedate=6 September 2010 }}</ref> This stage involves preliminary work to support the new line. It is centred on [[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield station]] and includes:\n\n* A ground-level car park at Seddon Park on the eastern side of the station. Construction commenced in May 2009 and was completed in October 2009.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110312092904/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/Our-Projects/Current-Projects/Commuter-Car-Park-Program/Glenfield--Seddon-Park-/Seddon-Park/default.aspx Seddon Park Commuter Car Park] [[Transport Construction Authority]]</ref>\n* A [[multi-storey car park]] on the western side of the station. Construction commenced in November 2009 and was completed in September 2010.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110308154420/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/News/Premier-and-Minister-for-Transport-officially-open-new-Glenfield-multi-storey-car-park/default.aspx Premier and Minister for Transport officially open new Glenfield multi-storey car park] [[Transport Construction Authority]]</ref>\n* The northern rail flyover. This replaced a [[Double junction|flat junction]] between the [[Main Southern railway line, New South Wales|Main South line]] and the [[East Hills railway line|East Hills line]] with a [[Flying junction|grade-separated junction]]. Construction commenced in June 2010 and was completed in June 2014.<ref name=SWRLglance>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110311013901/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/ArticleDocuments/91/SWRL%20at%20a%20glance.pdf.aspx South West Rail Link at a glance] Transport Construction Authority</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZweRqUdTfEc</ref>\n* An upgrade of Glenfield station including a new overhead concourse to replace a footbridge, construction of a fourth platform and a bus interchange. As part of this work, the existing platform 1 changed from a side turnback to a through platform. Construction commenced in late 2010 and was completed in mid-2014.\n\n====Stage two====\n[[File:Edmonson Park Railway Station Construction 1.jpg|thumb|[[Edmondson Park railway station|Edmondson Park station]] construction site in June 2012]]\n[[File:Leppington1.JPG|thumb|[[Leppington railway station|Leppington station]] entrance in February 2015]]\nStage two included extending the railway line westward towards Leppington. This involved:<ref name=CityRail3Dec09/>\n\n*A rail flyover on the south side of Glenfield station to take the new line over the [[Main Southern railway line|Main South line]] and the [[Southern Sydney Freight Line]].\n* 11.4 kilometres of double track from Glenfield to Leppington.\n*Stations and car parks at [[Edmondson Park railway station|Edmondson Park]] and [[Leppington railway station|Leppington]].\n*A new train stabling facility to the west of Leppington with a capacity for 20 8-car trains.<ref name=SWRLglance/>\n\nStage two received planning approval on 18 November 2010.<ref name=SWRLprofile /> On 7 December 2010, Premier [[Kristina Keneally]] announced that a contract for design and construction of stage two had been awarded to the [[John Holland Group]].<ref>{{cite news|title=$550 million South West Sydney Rail Link contract awarded |url=http://streetcorner.com.au/news/showPost.cfm?bid=20109&mycomm=SW |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302021645/http://streetcorner.com.au/news/showPost.cfm?bid=20109&mycomm=SW |archivedate=2 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September 2014, the NSW Government announced that construction was complete, saying the line had come in $300 million under budget and a year ahead of schedule.<ref>{{cite web|title=South West Rail Link construction complete, services to start in early 2015|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-construction-complete-services-start-early-2015|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=13 September 2014}}</ref> The line opened 8 February 2015.<ref>[http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2015/01/01/nsws-southwest-rail-link-open-soon NSW's southwest rail link to open soon] SBS 1 January 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.news.com.au/national/breaking-news/nsws-southwest-rail-link-to-open-soon/story-e6frfku9-1227171965445 NSW's southwest rail link to open soon] News.com.au 1 January 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/sydneys-new-rail-line-to-open-next-month/story-fni0cx12-1227172066593 Sydney\u2019s new rail line to open next month] ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Daily Telegraph]]'' 2 January 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-opens-customers-february-2015-one-year-ahead-schedule-and-300m South West Rail Link opens to customers in February 2015 - one year ahead of schedule and $300m under budget] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102105615/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-opens-customers-february-2015-one-year-ahead-schedule-and-300m |date=2 January 2015 }} Transport for NSW 2 January 2015</ref>\n\n====Associated projects====\nTwo associated projects affect the line.\n\nThe [[East Hills railway line|East Hills line's]] Kingsgrove to Revesby quadruplication [[Rail Clearways Program|Rail Clearways]] project opened in April 2013. It improved the capacity of the East Hills line by allowing the separation of express services to Leppington or [[Macarthur railway station|Macarthur]] from all-stops services to [[Revesby railway station|Revesby]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100908003910/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/Our-Projects/Current-Projects/Rail-Clearways-Program/Kingsgrove-to-Revesby-Quadruplication/Project-profile/default.aspx Rail Clearways Program - Kingsgrove to Revesby Quadruplication project profile] [[Transport Construction Authority]]</ref>\n\nThe [[Auburn Maintenance Centre|Auburn]] stabling project provided additional capacity to stable trains.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110311010011/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/ArticleDocuments/235/REF%20Volume%201%20-%20part%201.PDF.aspx Review of Environmental Factors - Part 1] page 4 [[Transport Construction Authority]]</ref>\n\n==Operation==\nOn 6 November 2014, the NSW Government announced that train testing had commenced on the line.<ref>{{cite web|title=First test trains hit the tracks on South West Rail Link|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/first-test-trains-hit-tracks-south-west-rail-link|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=6 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106125028/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/first-test-trains-hit-tracks-south-west-rail-link|archivedate=6 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Passenger services began on 8 February 2015, initially as a four carriage shuttle running every 30 minutes between [[Leppington railway station|Leppington]] and [[Liverpool railway station, Sydney|Liverpool]]. The shuttle stopped at all stations except [[Casula railway station|Casula]] and was also branded as the South West Rail Link. From 13 December 2015, trains operate as part of the [[Airport, Inner West & South Line]]. Some services operate to the city via Granville while others continue to terminate at Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web|title=South West Rail Link: Soon to head North and East, with more services|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-soon-head-north-and-east-more-services|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=15 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119041649/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-soon-head-north-and-east-more-services|archivedate=19 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Cumberland Line]] services to [[Schofields railway station|Schofields]] were introduced in 2017.<ref>[http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/liverpool-leader/southwest-sydney-train-service-to-increase-with-new-peak-hour-trains-and-northsouth-connection-from-leppington-to-parramatta-and-blacktown/news-story/d73b929edb43d030766ef7fb36eccf92 Southwest Sydney train service to increase with new peak hour trains and north-south connection from Leppington to Parramatta and Blacktown] ''Daily Telegraph'' 27 February 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/decision-on-rail-link-to-new-sydney-airport-many-years-off-transport-minister-andrew-constance-says-20170227-gum5rs.html Decision on rail link to new Sydney airport many years off, Transport Minister Andrew Constance says] ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' 27 February 2017</ref>\n\n== Extension proposals ==\nIt has been proposed that the line be extended from Leppington to the [[Western Sydney Airport]] at [[Badgerys Creek]].<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/badgerys-creek-railway-mapped-out-as-tony-abbott-promises-airport-decision-20140205-3211n.html Badgerys Creek railway mapped out as Tony Abbott promises airport decision] ''Sydney Morning Herald'' 5 February 2014</ref>\nHowever, as at 16 April 2014 the Federal Government has said it had no plans to build a train line. It did indicate a provision for the train line would be included in the development, this may include preparing the tunnels under the runway as part of the runway construction and preparing the underground space for a station.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saulwick|first=Jacob|title=Federal government plans for airport rail line but will not build it|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/federal-government-plans-for-airport-rail-line-but-will-not-build-it-20140416-zqvkk.html|accessdate=16 April 2014|newspaper=Brisbane Times|date=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the New South Wales government announced details for a plan to preserve corridors for extensions of the line. The government indicated it intends to preserve the corridors for the extensions but not to build them in the near future.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saulwick|first=Jacob|title=Six stations proposed for future train link to Badgerys Creek|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/six-stations-proposed-for-future-train-link-to-badgerys-creek-20140427-zr0f6.html|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=27 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=South West Rail Link Extension Corridor Protection|work=Transport for NSW - Projects|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429050952/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/projects-swrl-extension-corridor-protection|publisher=NSW Government|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom Leppington, the line would extend to [[Rossmore, New South Wales|Rossmore]], with a northern branch to [[Bringelly]] and a southern branch to [[Narellan]]. Proposed stations would be located at Rossmore, Bringelly, Maryland, [[Oran Park, New South Wales|Oran Park]] and Narellan. Preliminary investigations for an extension of the southern corridor from Narellan to the Main South railway line also commenced.<ref>{{cite web|title=South West Rail Link Extension - Public transport corridor preservation June 2015 - Consultation on Southern Section|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/projects/swrl-phase2-discussion-paper.pdf|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=9 June 2015|pages=4, 5, 12}}</ref>\n\nA scoping study into rail investment to service [[Western Sydney]] and the proposed Western Sydney Airport was announced by the New South Wales and Australian governments in November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Sydney Airport|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615185934/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/projects-western-sydney-airport|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=18 February 2016}}</ref> The study's final report was released in March 2018 and included a proposal to build a \"North-South Link\" from Schofields to Macarthur via the airport. The report also proposed an extension of the South West Rail Link from Leppington to the \"Badgerys Creek Aerotropolis\" - an area south of the airport. Passengers would need to interchange to access the airport itself.<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Sydney Rail Needs Scoping Study Outcomes Report|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306142557/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/system/files/media/documents/2018/wsrnsoutcome-report.pdf|publisher=Australian Government and New South Wales Government|accessdate=7 March 2018|pages=54-59|date=March 2018}}</ref> The North-South Link would use a similar corridor to the one being investigated for the extension of the South West Rail Link. This resulted in the corridor investigations into the South West Rail Link extensions being put on hold.<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Sydney Rail Needs Scoping Study Outcomes Report|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306142557/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/system/files/media/documents/2018/wsrnsoutcome-report.pdf|publisher=Australian Government and New South Wales Government|accessdate=7 March 2018|pages=47|date=March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transport in Sydney in the 2010s]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120718043920/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/projects-southwestraillink South West Rail Link]\n*[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/projects/TCA_SWRL_WebVideo_101029.wmv Flyover video of stage two]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060919095108/http://www.planning.nsw.gov.au/plansforaction/pdf/swrl.pdf South West Rail Link Overview Report] NSW Department of Planning (May 2005)\n*[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/projects/TCA_SWRL_at_a_glance.pdf.aspx TIDC: South West rail link project map]\n\n{{Sydney public transport}}\n{{Railway lines in New South Wales|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:South West Rail Link| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| box_width     = 300px\n| name          = '''South West Rail Link'''\n| other_name    = \n| native_name   = \n| native_name_lang = \n| color         = \n| logo          = \n| logo_width    = 200px\n| logo_alt      = \n| image         = New South Wales metropolitan rail area, with South West Rail Link highlighted.svg\n| image_width   = 300px\n| image_alt     = \n| caption       = New South Wales Metropolitan Rail Area with South West Rail Link shuttle highlighted in pink\n| type          = \n| system        = \n| status        = \n| locale        = \n| start         = [[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield]]\n| end           = [[Leppington railway station|Leppington]]\n| stations      = 3\n| routes        = [[Inner West & Leppington Line|T2 Inner West & Leppington]]<br>[[Cumberland Line|T5 Cumberland]]\n| daily_ridership = \n| ridership2    = \n| open          = {{Start date|2015|02|08|df=y}}\n| close         = \n| owner         = [[RailCorp]]\n| operator      = [[Sydney Trains]]\n| depot         = \n| stock         = \n| linelength_km =  11.4\n| gauge = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electrification = [[Overhead line|Overhead]] 1500 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]]<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.asa.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/asa/asa-standards/t-hr-el-00001-ti.pdf|title=RailCorp electrical system general description, version 1.0|date=19 March 2014|author=Asset Standards Authority}}</ref>\n| speed =\n| website       = \n| map           = {{South West Rail Link RDT}}\n| map_state     = collapsed\n}}\n\nThe '''South West Rail Link''' is a railway line serving the developing suburbs of [[south-western Sydney]], Australia. Services form part of the [[Sydney Trains]] [[commuter rail]] network. It opened on 8 February 2015.\n\n==Description==\nThe line consists of a {{convert|11.4|km|abbr=on}} double-track railway, with stations in the suburbs of [[Leppington]] and [[Edmondson Park]]. The line is the major piece of public transport infrastructure for the Sydney metropolitan area's \"South West Growth Centre\". It connects with the rest of the Sydney rail network at [[Glenfield, New South Wales|Glenfield]], where services can continue north on the [[Main Southern railway line|Main South line]] or east on the [[East Hills railway line|East Hills line]]. Leppington station's four platforms can support frequent terminating services, even after an extension of the line. A train stabling facility to the west of the station further enhances this capability. Development of the project was managed by [[Transport for New South Wales]] and its predecessor, the [[Transport Construction Authority]].\n\n==History==\n===Conception===\nThe South West Rail Link was originally part of the Metropolitan Rail Expansion Program (MREP) proposed by the [[Bob Carr|Carr Government]] in 2005,<ref>{{cite news|last=Besser|first=Linton|title=Bye heavy rail, now for a north-west metro|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/bye-heavy-rail-now-for-a-northwest-metro/2008/02/25/1203788248514.html|accessdate=14 June 2011|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=26 February 2008}}</ref> along with the [[North West railway line, Sydney|North West Rail Link]] and the [[Redfern to Chatswood railway line|CBD rail link]]. The three projects were to be integrated into a single operational sector, with trains from the south-west running to the north-west via the CBD Link. The other two components of the MREP were cancelled in 2008, but the South West Rail Link remained on the government's agenda. Plans for the North West Rail Link were resurrected in 2011 and the rail link was completed in 2019, forming part of the [[Sydney Metro]] network.\n\nIn March 2008, the [[Morris Iemma|Iemma Government]] indicated that construction would begin in 2009, with completion scheduled for 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=New $1.36b rail link on time: Iemma|url= http://news.smh.com.au/national/new-136b-rail-link-on-time-iemma-20080306-1xe9.html|accessdate=14 June 2011|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=6 March 2008}}</ref> By October of that year the government had decided that delivery of the project would be divided into two stages. Stage one would comprise preliminary work around [[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield station]], and stage two would comprise construction of the new line itself, stage two was deferred due to budget cuts.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benson |first=Simon |title=Northwest Metro rail link officially shelved |url=http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24579596-5001021,00.html |accessdate=14 June 2011 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=31 October 2008 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081103115958/http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,24579596-5001021,00.html |archivedate=3 November 2008 }}</ref> On 14 November 2009, Premier [[Nathan Rees]] announced that construction of stage two of the South West Rail Link would begin in mid-2010, with completion scheduled for 2016.<ref name=CityRail3Dec09>[http://cityrail.info/news/2009/091203-southwest Green light for South West rail link Stage 2] [[CityRail]], 3 December 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Axed $1.3b south-west rail link revived|url=http://www.smh.com.au/national/axed-13b-southwest-rail-link-revived-20091113-iept.html|accessdate=14 June 2011|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 November 2009|last1=Clennell|first1=Andrew|last2=Robins|first2=Brian}}</ref>\n\n===Construction===\n====Stage one====\n[[File:Glenfield Railway Station Concourse Exterior.jpg|thumb|[[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield station]] new concourse building in December 2012]]\n[[File:Glenfield railway station carpark from south.jpg|thumb|[[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield station]] new multi-storey commuter car park in November 2011]]\nPlanning approval for stage one of the project was received in April 2009.<ref name=SWRLprofile>{{cite web|title=Project profile |url=http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/Our-Projects/Current-Projects/South-West-Rail-Link/Project-Profile/Project-profile/default.aspx|publisher=Transport Construction Authority |accessdate=14 June 2011 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906084033/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/Our-Projects/Current-Projects/South-West-Rail-Link/Project-Profile/Project-profile/default.aspx|archivedate=6 September 2010 }}</ref> This stage involves preliminary work to support the new line. It is centred on [[Glenfield railway station, Sydney|Glenfield station]] and includes:\n\n* A ground-level car park at Seddon Park on the eastern side of the station. Construction commenced in May 2009 and was completed in October 2009.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110312092904/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/Our-Projects/Current-Projects/Commuter-Car-Park-Program/Glenfield--Seddon-Park-/Seddon-Park/default.aspx Seddon Park Commuter Car Park] [[Transport Construction Authority]]</ref>\n* A [[multi-storey car park]] on the western side of the station. Construction commenced in November 2009 and was completed in September 2010.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110308154420/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/News/Premier-and-Minister-for-Transport-officially-open-new-Glenfield-multi-storey-car-park/default.aspx Premier and Minister for Transport officially open new Glenfield multi-storey car park] [[Transport Construction Authority]]</ref>\n* The northern rail flyover. This replaced a [[Double junction|flat junction]] between the [[Main Southern railway line, New South Wales|Main South line]] and the [[East Hills railway line|East Hills line]] with a [[Flying junction|grade-separated junction]]. Construction commenced in June 2010 and was completed in June 2014.<ref name=SWRLglance>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110311013901/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/ArticleDocuments/91/SWRL%20at%20a%20glance.pdf.aspx South West Rail Link at a glance] Transport Construction Authority</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZweRqUdTfEc</ref>\n* An upgrade of Glenfield station including a new overhead concourse to replace a footbridge, construction of a fourth platform and a bus interchange. As part of this work, the existing platform 1 changed from a side turnback to a through platform. Construction commenced in late 2010 and was completed in mid-2014.\n\n====Stage two====\n[[File:Edmonson Park Railway Station Construction 1.jpg|thumb|[[Edmondson Park railway station|Edmondson Park station]] construction site in June 2012]]\n[[File:Leppington1.JPG|thumb|[[Leppington railway station|Leppington station]] entrance in February 2015]]\nStage two included extending the railway line westward towards Leppington. This involved:<ref name=CityRail3Dec09/>\n\n*A rail flyover on the south side of Glenfield station to take the new line over the [[Main Southern railway line|Main South line]] and the [[Southern Sydney Freight Line]].\n* 11.4 kilometres of double track from Glenfield to Leppington.\n*Stations and car parks at [[Edmondson Park railway station|Edmondson Park]] and [[Leppington railway station|Leppington]].\n*A new train stabling facility to the west of Leppington with a capacity for 20 8-car trains.<ref name=SWRLglance/>\n\nStage two received planning approval on 18 November 2010.<ref name=SWRLprofile /> On 7 December 2010, Premier [[Kristina Keneally]] announced that a contract for design and construction of stage two had been awarded to the [[John Holland Group]].<ref>{{cite news|title=$550 million South West Sydney Rail Link contract awarded |url=http://streetcorner.com.au/news/showPost.cfm?bid=20109&mycomm=SW |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302021645/http://streetcorner.com.au/news/showPost.cfm?bid=20109&mycomm=SW |archivedate=2 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 13 September 2014, the NSW Government announced that construction was complete, saying the line had come in $300 million under budget and a year ahead of schedule.<ref>{{cite web|title=South West Rail Link construction complete, services to start in early 2015|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-construction-complete-services-start-early-2015|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=13 September 2014}}</ref> The line opened 8 February 2015.<ref>[http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2015/01/01/nsws-southwest-rail-link-open-soon NSW's southwest rail link to open soon] SBS 1 January 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.news.com.au/national/breaking-news/nsws-southwest-rail-link-to-open-soon/story-e6frfku9-1227171965445 NSW's southwest rail link to open soon] News.com.au 1 January 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/sydneys-new-rail-line-to-open-next-month/story-fni0cx12-1227172066593 Sydney\u2019s new rail line to open next month] ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|Daily Telegraph]]'' 2 January 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-opens-customers-february-2015-one-year-ahead-schedule-and-300m South West Rail Link opens to customers in February 2015 - one year ahead of schedule and $300m under budget] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150102105615/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-opens-customers-february-2015-one-year-ahead-schedule-and-300m |date=2 January 2015 }} Transport for NSW 2 January 2015</ref>\n\n====Associated projects====\nTwo associated projects affect the line.\n\nThe [[East Hills railway line|East Hills line's]] Kingsgrove to Revesby quadruplication [[Rail Clearways Program|Rail Clearways]] project opened in April 2013. It improved the capacity of the East Hills line by allowing the separation of express services to Leppington or [[Macarthur railway station|Macarthur]] from all-stops services to [[Revesby railway station|Revesby]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100908003910/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/Our-Projects/Current-Projects/Rail-Clearways-Program/Kingsgrove-to-Revesby-Quadruplication/Project-profile/default.aspx Rail Clearways Program - Kingsgrove to Revesby Quadruplication project profile] [[Transport Construction Authority]]</ref>\n\nThe [[Auburn Maintenance Centre|Auburn]] stabling project provided additional capacity to stable trains.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110311010011/http://www.tca.nsw.gov.au/ArticleDocuments/235/REF%20Volume%201%20-%20part%201.PDF.aspx Review of Environmental Factors - Part 1] page 4 [[Transport Construction Authority]]</ref>\n\n==Operation==\nOn 6 November 2014, the NSW Government announced that train testing had commenced on the line.<ref>{{cite web|title=First test trains hit the tracks on South West Rail Link|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/first-test-trains-hit-tracks-south-west-rail-link|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=6 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106125028/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/first-test-trains-hit-tracks-south-west-rail-link|archivedate=6 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Passenger services began on 8 February 2015, initially as a four carriage shuttle running every 30 minutes between [[Leppington railway station|Leppington]] and [[Liverpool railway station, Sydney|Liverpool]]. The shuttle stopped at all stations except [[Casula railway station|Casula]] and was also branded as the South West Rail Link. From 13 December 2015, trains operate as part of the [[Airport, Inner West & South Line]]. Some services operate to the city via Granville while others continue to terminate at Liverpool.<ref>{{cite web|title=South West Rail Link: Soon to head North and East, with more services|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-soon-head-north-and-east-more-services|publisher=Transport for NSW|date=15 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119041649/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/media-releases/south-west-rail-link-soon-head-north-and-east-more-services|archivedate=19 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Cumberland Line]] services to [[Schofields railway station|Schofields]] were introduced in 2017.<ref>[http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/liverpool-leader/southwest-sydney-train-service-to-increase-with-new-peak-hour-trains-and-northsouth-connection-from-leppington-to-parramatta-and-blacktown/news-story/d73b929edb43d030766ef7fb36eccf92 Southwest Sydney train service to increase with new peak hour trains and north-south connection from Leppington to Parramatta and Blacktown] ''Daily Telegraph'' 27 February 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/decision-on-rail-link-to-new-sydney-airport-many-years-off-transport-minister-andrew-constance-says-20170227-gum5rs.html Decision on rail link to new Sydney airport many years off, Transport Minister Andrew Constance says] ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' 27 February 2017</ref>\n\n== Extension proposals ==\nIt has been proposed that the line be extended from Leppington to the [[Western Sydney Airport]] at [[Badgerys Creek]].<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/badgerys-creek-railway-mapped-out-as-tony-abbott-promises-airport-decision-20140205-3211n.html Badgerys Creek railway mapped out as Tony Abbott promises airport decision] ''Sydney Morning Herald'' 5 February 2014</ref>\nHowever, as at 16 April 2014 the Federal Government has said it had no plans to build a train line. It did indicate a provision for the train line would be included in the development, this may include preparing the tunnels under the runway as part of the runway construction and preparing the underground space for a station.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saulwick|first=Jacob|title=Federal government plans for airport rail line but will not build it|url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/federal-government-plans-for-airport-rail-line-but-will-not-build-it-20140416-zqvkk.html|accessdate=16 April 2014|newspaper=Brisbane Times|date=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, the New South Wales government announced details for a plan to preserve corridors for extensions of the line. The government indicated it intends to preserve the corridors for the extensions but not to build them in the near future.<ref>{{cite news|last=Saulwick|first=Jacob|title=Six stations proposed for future train link to Badgerys Creek|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/six-stations-proposed-for-future-train-link-to-badgerys-creek-20140427-zr0f6.html|accessdate=28 April 2014|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=27 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=South West Rail Link Extension Corridor Protection|work=Transport for NSW - Projects|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429050952/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/projects-swrl-extension-corridor-protection|publisher=NSW Government|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nFrom Leppington, the line would extend to [[Rossmore, New South Wales|Rossmore]], with a northern branch to [[Bringelly]] and a southern branch to [[Narellan]]. Proposed stations would be located at Rossmore, Bringelly, Maryland, [[Oran Park, New South Wales|Oran Park]] and Narellan. Preliminary investigations for an extension of the southern corridor from Narellan to the Main South railway line also commenced.<ref>{{cite web|title=South West Rail Link Extension - Public transport corridor preservation June 2015 - Consultation on Southern Section|url=http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/projects/swrl-phase2-discussion-paper.pdf|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=9 June 2015|pages=4, 5, 12}}</ref>\n\nA scoping study into rail investment to service [[Western Sydney]] and the proposed Western Sydney Airport was announced by the New South Wales and Australian governments in November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Sydney Airport|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160615185934/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/projects-western-sydney-airport|publisher=Transport for NSW|accessdate=18 February 2016}}</ref> The study's final report was released in March 2018 and included a proposal to build a \"North-South Link\" from Schofields to Macarthur via the airport. The report also proposed an extension of the South West Rail Link from Leppington to the \"Badgerys Creek Aerotropolis\" - an area south of the airport. Passengers would need to interchange to access the airport itself.<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Sydney Rail Needs Scoping Study Outcomes Report|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306142557/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/system/files/media/documents/2018/wsrnsoutcome-report.pdf|publisher=Australian Government and New South Wales Government|accessdate=7 March 2018|pages=54-59|date=March 2018}}</ref> The North-South Link would use a similar corridor to the one being investigated for the extension of the South West Rail Link. This resulted in the corridor investigations into the South West Rail Link extensions being put on hold.<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Sydney Rail Needs Scoping Study Outcomes Report|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306142557/https://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/system/files/media/documents/2018/wsrnsoutcome-report.pdf|publisher=Australian Government and New South Wales Government|accessdate=7 March 2018|pages=47|date=March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transport in Sydney in the 2010s]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120718043920/http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/projects-southwestraillink South West Rail Link]\n*[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/projects/TCA_SWRL_WebVideo_101029.wmv Flyover video of stage two]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060919095108/http://www.planning.nsw.gov.au/plansforaction/pdf/swrl.pdf South West Rail Link Overview Report] NSW Department of Planning (May 2005)\n*[http://www.transport.nsw.gov.au/sites/default/files/b2b/projects/TCA_SWRL_at_a_glance.pdf.aspx TIDC: South West rail link project map]\n\n{{Sydney public transport}}\n{{Railway lines in New South Wales|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:South West Rail Link| ]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Rangasyd", "label": "safe", "comment": "removedCategory:Standard gauge railways in AustraliausingHotCatduplicated category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_West_Rail_Link"}
